<a name="What_is_this_all_about.3F_Why_a_tutorial_about_filetypes.3F"></a><h2> What is this all about? Why a tutorial about filetypes? </h2>
<p>Since there seems to be a lot of absolute newbies to the Doom 3 modding community, some questions are cropping up again and again. I have seen some info posted about this beginners stuff, but this were posted also by other beginners and therfefore there is a lot of wrong or missleading information floating around. Therefore I decided to clear thing up and hopefully help beginners to get a better understanding of what modding means, especially with regards to coding within the SDK.
</p><p>The purpose of this tutorial is to explain the various filetypes relevant to Doom 3 modding, and is intended for absolute beginners. If you are such a beginner and you don't understand what it means then post a question in the Doom 3 forum for coding and I try to add a better explanation here. Since I'm a professional programmer for more then 20 years now, and by no means I'm a teacher kind of guy, my tutorial may be to advanced without me realizing because this stuff is second nature to me by now. Therfore if something is not explained well it may be because I didn't realize that it should be better explained.
</p>
<a name="Introduction"></a><h2> Introduction </h2>
<p>On computers there exists many different filetypes where each of them serves a specific purpose. Files are just a collection containing data, and to the computer it doesn't matter what a file exactly contains, because this is only relevant to an application that tries to load the data and work with it. Nevertheless, to make it easier for humans to work with this files, there have been established some format and conventions. The data in a file can be split into binary and non-binary data. Binary data means that a single byte may contain a character which is in the range of 0-255 while non-binary data is limited to a specific range. In order to have human readable text to be recognized, there exists some standardizations. The one rather common and relevant for us is ASCII. There exists some others like EBCDIC, but this is mainly used on mainframes and don't need to concern us here.
ASCII data contains a subset of the binary characters, which can be printed (for exmaple on a printer), or control some aspect of the printing or display (like FormFeed, LineFeed, etc.). The control characters are also printable, but don't neccessarily translate to a readable character, and perform some function instead.
Example: The FormFeed character should, when inserted in a text, force the printer to go the the next page before continuing printing.
The standard set of ASCII characters are in the range between 0-127. There exists exceptions in order to support foreign country characters like the Umlaute for german language, which are located above 127. Only the character between 0 and 127 are really standardized. All others may vary depending on language settings. For a reference on ASCII character you can take a look at this <a href="/web/20070729231805/http://www.lookuptables.com/" class='external text' title="http://www.lookuptables.com/">ASCII Table</a>.
</p><p>Commonly we refer to a file as text file when it consists only of characters between 1 and 127. 0 is ommited because it is not printable. Most editors, like Notepad will consider a file also as valid textfile when it contains characters above because of the above mentioned language settings. 
A binary file is a file that contains all characters wihtout regard of language settings. These files can also be loaded into a texteditor like Notepad. <b>BUT</b> you will not see the entire file in it, because a texteditor can not print non-printable characters (otherwise they would be printable&nbsp;:) ). <b>And most important!</b> If you load a binary file into a texteditor and try to save it, the save will be corrupted. Depending on the editor it may work, but you should not count on it. So NEVER try to load a binary file into an editor, edit some text in there and save it, ebcause the result is most likely unusable.
</p>
<a name="How_do_you_know_wether_a_file_is_binary_or_not.3F"></a><h2> How do you know wether a file is binary or not? </h2>
<p>In order to determine what kind of file it is there are two ways to find this out. One is to look at it's extentsion (which is the part after the '.' like "system32.dll" which indicates a DLL file. If you use Windows Explorer and you didn't switch on to show the extensions, then you may not see this. So I suggest switching on this option so you can always clearly see what type a file is. The method of looking at the extension is pretty unreliable though. As I explained above, you can store any kind of data into a file. The extension is just a convetion. In most cases it will be followed, but it doesn't have to. So I can easily create a file named "MyText.dll" with notepad and write a letter in there, and it would be a textfile only, while the extension of DLL would indicate a binary executable file. This is not recommended though, because abusing files like this will only confuse you, your system and may cause unwanted side effects.
The second method of determing what kind a file is, is to look at it with a hex editor/viewer. If you don't have one, then you can easily find one by looking on google for "hex viewer download" or any of the major downloadsites with shareware tools. When you open an arbitrary file with such a hex viewer, you will see usually 16 columns with values like this:
</p>
<pre>00 FE 31 ...
</pre>
<p>From what we learned above, we can now determine wether a file is binary or not simply by looking at some of these values. If there are values like 0 and FE, as in the above example, you can be pretty sure that it is a binary file. If it contains text you will easily see it when loading it in an texteditor, but this can be missleading. Notepad would display all printable characters and silently suppress the other ones. But you can still get an estimate if the text is interspersed with strange character or strangely formated. the surest way though is to look at it with an ehexeditor.
</p>
<a name="Why_is_this_relevant_for_Doom_3_modding_and_why_should_I_care.3F"></a><h2> Why is this relevant for Doom 3 modding and why should I care? </h2>
<p>You should know about this simply because Doom 3 uses text and binary files depending on the purpose of the specific files. Since I told you above that a file can get corrupted when it is binary but saved with a texteditor it will get corrupted and consequently will be unusable. Some files need to be binary and some file need to be text, while other may be binary or text.
</p>
<a name="How_do_I_create_these_files_and_what_should_I_take_care_of_with_them.3F"></a><h2> How do I create these files and what should I take care of with them? </h2>
<p>A textfile can be created with any texteditor. You can use a simple one like notepad, or a more sophisticated one like Xemacs, UltraEditor or any other editor out there. One thing should be observed though. There is a small difference between textfiles on Unix and on Windows and also other operating systems. Why should you care about this? Simply because Doom 3 runs on other systems as well, like Linux and Mac. If you use the wrong format, then your mod may or may not run on this other system and it would be a shame to limit your audience for such a simple reason.
The difference is how editors usually treat the end of a line. On Unix there is only one character needed to set the end of line which is CR ( Carriage Return). On Windows many programs use CR+LF (Carriage Return + Line Feed)
This is inserted by your texteditor whenever you press the RETURN key and will do it correct for your operating system. Many editors have an option which one you want and there are also converters to translate between one format and the others. Depending on your application it may or may not work correctly with all kind of formats.
</p><p>Binary files, on the other hand, are always created with a special application. The content of a binary file is only machine readable and therefore the content dependent on the application. For example: All 3D apps usually create binary files to store your models and material definitions and so on, inside a binary file, but this is not neccessarily so. There exists a number of 3D file formats, which are plain ASCII as well.
</p>
<a name="Which_type_of_file_should_I_use_and_why.3F"></a><h2> Which type of file should I use and why? </h2>
<p>That depends on your needs. If your application only supports on kind of file, then the choice is made and you can't change that. If you have the choice between any format it depends on what else you want to do with it. As I said above, a binar file is not human readable. It can be read and used directly by the computer without the need of translating it. Loading times are therfore usually faster with binary files. On the other hand, if you use an ASCII format, you can extend it more easily and add new stuff to it without causing problems in the code. If you need to verify that your application reads and save correct it is much easier then with a binary file. But as I said, an ASCII file needs to be translated if it should be used by the computer.
For example, if you have a brush stored in an ASCII file (like Doom 3 does with it's MAP files), then it contains all the relevant numbers for the 3D space. But these numbers are just text and the computer can not calculate with them, so they have to be ocnverted to real numbers before the CPU can start calculating with them.
Example:
You store three colours in a textfile in R, G, B order then it may look like this:
</p>
<pre>12 212 178 
</pre>
<p>If you store the same information in a binary file and look at it with an hex viewer it would look like this:
</p>
<pre>0C D4 B2
</pre>
<p>So if you want to do some calculations with these colours, then you need to translate it from the text 12 into the value 12 which is C in hex.
</p>
<a name="Which_filestypes_are_used_in_Doom_3_.3F"></a><h2> Which filestypes are used in Doom 3&nbsp;? </h2>
<p>Doom 3 uses a mixture of binary files and ASCII files. Virtuall all of the files that contain game asset data are ASCII files. This is rather advantagous for modders because they can easily change them without an extra application. A variety of files are binary though, which is either out of neccessity or because it offers other advantages. Most notibly the game executable Doom3.exe is a binary file because this can not be something else. Also the gamex86.dll is a binary file, because it is, similar to the EXE file, a binary file by nature. Other files that are binary are the PK4 files which are just renamed ZIP files, OGG files which contain sounds, LWO files which are models created with the Lightwave 3D suite, and MB files which are Maya 3D models and all the image formats for the textures like TGA, JPG and so on. This list is not neccessarily exhaustive though.
Most other files are ASCII. Most notibly, the DEF files which contain all kind of game definitions for weapons, models, etc., MTR files which contain material definitions, MAP files which contain the map layout that you can create with the editor when creating a new map, and so on. This list is also not exhaustive, and you can find out about these files when browsing either your D3 directory or look into the PK4 files.
</p><div class="printfooter">
